      "createdAt": "2026-03-24T12:58:03.547012+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "James, please don't apologize. It takes real courage to say what you just said, and I'm genuinely glad you told me.\n\nWhat you're describing — pushing through pain, feeling embarrassed, worrying you've made things worse — that's a really hard place to be. And the fact that you came forward with it now matters. That's the decision that counts.\n\n---\n\nI do need to be straight with you about something, and I want you to hear it as care, not criticism: diagnosing what's happening with your foot and telling you how to treat it is outside what I'm qualified to do. I'm your running coach, not a medical professional, and plantar fasciitis that's worsening with activity — especially to the point of stopping you mid-run — genuinely needs a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor to assess it. They can see what's actually going on in a way I simply can't.\n\n**What I'd ask you to do this week:** Contact your physio and describe exactly what you told me — that the pain has been worsening, that you've had to stop the last three runs, and that you're concerned it's progressed. The sooner they can see you, the sooner we know what we're actually working with.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I want you to hold onto: **this is not the end of your return.** It's a detour, and detours have routes back. The fitness you built before the injury doesn't disappear. The consistency you showed in those early return runs — that was real, and it tells me something important about who you are as a runner.\n\nOnce you have guidance from your physio, I'll be right here to rebuild a plan around whatever they clear you for — even if that's walking only for a while. We work with what we have, and we move forward from there.\n\nCan you reach out to your physio today or tomorrow?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01AwjvqGkyD7aeSfDex8fTP8"
    }
  ],
